<DOC><DOCNO> AP890208-0125 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 1337EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-China-Art     02-08 0277</FIRST><SECOND>AM-China-Art,0284</SECOND><HEAD>Police Release Pair Held in Art Gallery Shooting</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police on Wednesday released an artist afterholding her three days for shooting a BB gun at her own sculpture inan exhibition of avant-garde art, the official Xinhua News Agencysaid.   The exhibit, the largest modern art show in communist China's40-year history, was closed by police a few hours after it openedSunday when Xiao Lu opened fire at her model of a phone booth.   Xinhua said the Beijing Public Security Bureau ordered Ms. Xiaoand her boyfriend, Tang Songmang, detained five days as punishmentfor disturbing public order. Tang, 28, tried to help Ms. Xiao, 25,smuggle her gun from the China Art Gallery, Xinhua said.   However, the report said police decided to release them afterthree days as a concession in honor of the Lunar New Year holiday,called Spring Festival. Monday began the new Year of the Snake, butthe official holiday lasts through Wednesday.   Xinhua said Ms. Xiao acknowledged shooting at her sculpture, butsaid it was because she thought it was imperfect and needed``destructive art.''   An exhibition organizer, Fei Dawei, said Monday it was Tang whoactually fired at the work. He said they ``were attempting to negatemodern civilization'' and called the action ``performance art.''Authorities had banned performance art from the show in advance,saying it might cause chaos.   Fei said the show might reopen Friday. Xinhua did not comment onthe show's fate.   Xinhua said Chinese regulations allow detention of up to 15 daysfor disturbing public order. Police can impose detention sentenceswithout trial or opportunity for the accused to appeal.</TEXT></DOC>